data.title: So I did shrooms for the first time...

images.description:
So I tried shrooms for the first time because I am bored out of my mind during this quarantine. I thought to myself “hey I got a good head over my shoulders and I am really healthy, so why not try it?”. But before trying, I did my my research and found out it is mostly harmless and it is in fact safer than most other substances like cocaine, alcohol and weed.

In fact, the scientific community suggests that it may be more effective at helping people fight depression, ptsd, anxiety, and other sad stuff than many pharmaceutical drugs.

As you can see, I pulled this from a Lancet article (I think it’s the Lancet scientific journal) and it suggests that it’s way less harmful to others and yourself than alcohol. 

I don’t want to delve too much into the science of this. I want to tell you how it feels.

All your senses are heightened.

Sight: This is what most people are expecting when taking shrooms but after trying it for the first time I can tell you that you don’t see colourful pastel light emitting everywhere. You start to see some patterns move (very subtle, not some Michael Bay shit exploding everywhere). 

Hearing: Music becomes more euphoric; your mind becomes so creative that you think you see music and it makes everything sound nice. I even listened to classical music and I was head banging. 

Taste: I ate some cake and I was fucking losing it. It was so good and I never realized the texture feel made it so amazing! I felt like I could almost deconstruct every ingredient in it.

Touch: soft things feel softer, showering feels like you taking a soak in a bath/hot spring. For some reason, any surface that is slightly warm feels extremely hot and uncomfortable. I was sweating after lying in the same bed position for 2 minutes that felt like an eternity.

data.title: Kevin McCarthy skewered in fact-check after trying to blame Trump-era spending on Biden

images.description:
On Thursday, Washington Post fact-checker Salvador Rizzo quashed the claim by House Minority Leader Kevin McCarthy (R-CA) that the previous debt ceiling hike Republicans backed in 2019 "paid for everything in the Trump administration, plus seven months of this Biden administration."

However, wrote Rizzo, McCarthy's claim is wrong because the debt ceiling is actually just an authorization to pay bills already accrued, and the spending was a result of programs that were already approved prior to the Biden administration taking office.

"The claim is highly misleading," wrote Rizzo. "Regularly paying the monthly bill on your car or house doesn't mean you've paid the entire sticker price. The same goes for government policies such as Trump's 2017 tax cuts, which the government continues to borrow hundreds of billions of dollars a year to finance."

I've worked 3 days and recorded more than 30,000 snapshots to make this detailed picture of the Moon (zoom in!)

images.description:
As in my other Moon pictures, I took several videos with my iNova PLB Cx camera mounted on an 150/1800mm telescope. Due to the small sensor of the camera, I only see a little part of the Moon, that's why I take several videos to cover the whole Moon. I have then extracted the pictures from the videos, aligned/stacked the 5% best quality frames, and have finally merged all the images to made this picture of the Moon.

All my work is on my Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/astronophilos Every following means a lot, thank you :)

PS: The background is a Milky Way picture in which I've added a blur effect. Stars have been observed on another part of the sky and added in processing.

data.description:
Republican U.S. Rep. Lauren Boebert paid rent and utility bills with campaign funds in violation of federal campaign finance laws, new filings with the Federal Election Commision show.

Each of the four payments in question (two for $2,000 each and another two for $1,325 each) were amended to show payments for the same amount, description and on the same days to John Pacheco, whose address is the same as Shooters Grill in Rifle, which Boebert owns. Pacheco’s relationship to Boebert was not immediately clear.

The filings, submitted to the FEC on Tuesday, also indicate that Boebert reimbursed her campaign for the $6,650 worth of payments. Representatives for the congresswoman could not immediately be reached for comment.

data.title: Federal judge: Florida immigration law racially motivated

images.description:
The office of Gov. Ron DeSantis, who signed the bill into law with much fanfare in 2019 as a priority of his administration, said Wednesday that it would appeal.

Judge Bloom said that the law was racially motivated and that its supporters showed no evidence as to why it was needed to lower crime. She said that the sponsor of the bill — SB 168 — was guided by anti-immigrant hate groups such as Floridians for Immigration Enforcement.

“Allowing anti-immigrant hate groups that overtly promote xenophobic, nationalist, racist ideologies to be intimately involved in a bill’s legislative process is a significant departure from procedural norms,” Bloom wrote. “This involvement strongly suggests that the Legislature enacted SB 168 to promote and ratify the racist views of these advocacy groups.”

images.description:
Starting from my passion for saltwater aquaria, I have taken about a 13x20' chunk of my basement to develop propagation techniques, collect difference species and learn the optimal growing environments for our salty friends.  

Amongst many other marine species, there are three main types of corals, Soft Corals, Large Polyp Stony corals (LPS), and Small Polyp Stony corals (SPS).  I'll spare a lot of the techno-babble and get onto the pretty colours...

Kindly bear with me, as reef photography is tricky due to the intense blue lighting (which makes the colours pop).  We'll start with Soft Corals!  Soft Corals are classified as such due to their soft tissue body with not skeleton.  Some Soft Corals, however, do gather sand and substrate and incorporate it into their body.  Soft Corals are very easy to keep and can be housed in the most basic of salt water tanks.
Here we have a colony of "Clove Polyps" (Clavularia sp.), I keep four different colours, two are pictured.
These are small "Hairy Mushrooms" (Rhodactis Howesii), they are slightly larger than a toonie (maybe 1.5" diameter).  I have another variety which gets up to 5" diameter.

data.title: 6 months of work, chainmail coif done!

images.description: Today I finally finished my chainmail coif! Each ring is individually riveted. This is the strongest kind of chainmail you can make with the 4in1 pattern. It took me almost 6 months. Lots of time went into riveting each ring, easily took a couple weeks. You  only can rivet so many rings before your hands start to strain and need to take a break for the rest of the day.

It goes over the shoulders and also covers a bit of the upper torso. Done it like this because I wanted to close every gap on the upper body with my chainmail. It also is the more historically accurate way.
Chainmail coif in detail while worn. Feel free to zoom in to see each riveted ring. Don't ask me how many went into there. Too many is the answer!

data.title: My Science Fair Contribution is a Summary of the Interview I did with Kim Crow. The First Woman to Have Her Voice Digitized for the Cockpit Warning System ... (She's the Original Bitchin' Betty)

images.description: I love aviation, and the engineering behind it. Long story short, I got involved with an online community with like minded people, and got a chance to meet some cool people like Chuck Yeager and Kim Crow.

So who is Kim Crow? Why is it a big deal her voice was digitized and why is it part of the science fair?

Kim Crow is an Emmy nominated voice actress. The big deal about her voice being digitized, is because it was part of a, then classified, system being rolled for new aircraft. These news planes were much faster, more complex, and pilots needed something other than "idiot lights" to help keep them safe. Her voice was used for an audio warning system that has saved lives.

See this was back in the 1960s when all this was going down and in those days, a lot of things were being done reel to reel. Not only was her voice being used in military aircraft, but she was doing things for the space program too. Even then they were very interested in going to Mars.

Her voice would've been the voice for a computer system that would do things such as greet the mission commander, and help communicate with Earth. Of course that project didn't go anywhere. On the upside the last time we spoke she was asked to record for a new attraction NASA was working on. She couldn't give me details ... NDA type stuff.

It's been years since I worked for a movie theater but somethings really stick with you. Homemade carmel corn anyone?

images.description:
I currently use a non corn syrup and no bake recipe: 

1 cup butter, melted (I get it soft in the microwave first) 
1 cup of light brown sugar 
2 tbsp of vanilla extract (1 1/2 tbsp provides a little lighter of a vanilla taste)
1/2 tsp of baking powder

Prep your popcorn first! If you want to be a little bit lazy just pop two bags of microwave popcorn. (Honestly works just as well!)

If you want the fresh popped on the stove just follow the packaging instructions on the back and when it's popped add a little salt over it (if you want)

On medium to medium low heat, melt the butter in a pan and mix the brown sugar. Continue to whisk until the mixture begins to bubble. Set a timer for 5 minutes and keep an eye on the mixture. The last 2 minutes add the vanilla extract and wisk it together (be warned its hot and may splatter), the last minute add the baking powder and whisk together. 

The mixture is going to look a little funky (like a thick brown foam) when you go to pour it don't worry that's normally! 

Pour the mixture over the popcorn and mix it together with a spatula (the rubber ones for baking) and lay it out over a baking sheet (I highly recommend having parchment paper on top of the baking sheet!)

Let it cool and enjoy!

**Edited as much as I could for spelling mistakes. Ignore the title I know it's supposed to be caramel**

data.title: Wanna learn about measuring the ocean?

tags.name: sciencefair
tags.description: Share your love for the sciences in this two-week celebration of STEM! Tag your post with #ScienceFair to earn the trophy.

images.description: CTDs are some of the most common and essential instruments used in oceanography. They measure Conductivity (for salinity),  Temperature, and Depth all the way down to the bottom or a specified depth. Other sensors are also often included for chlorophyll or dissolved oxygen levels. Many,  like this one, have a live connection to the ship so data can be recorded in real time. The data essentially creates a profile of the water column at the location of the cast.

The whole CTD! The gray cylinders are open on both ends and can be triggered to close at any point so water samples can be collected from any depth or point of interest. The actual CTD sensors are in the center. The thing on the right is a benthic grab on a stand. These are lowered to the seafloor where they grab a section of the soil's surface.
This is the ALVIN submersible! At the time of this picture it was being modified for even deeper trips.
